The Triple-Ledger Gap is the archival discrepancy at the Wizard's Keep where three expected ledger streams fail to reconcile across a key historical window.
The Keep's operating doctrine requires all sanctioned arcane operations to produce three records: the practical ledger (what was attempted), the witness ledger (who observed), and the consequence ledger (what changed, including casualties and anomalies).
The Gap refers to a specific period in the Keep's history where operations documented in the practical ledger have no corresponding witness entries, and the consequence ledger for that period shows evidence of selective destruction rather than normal archival wear.
A procedure without all three ledgers is invalid in doctrine, even when tactically successful — the Gap therefore represents an unknown number of operations that are formally undocumented even though they occurred.
The Burnt Records Incident is associated with the Gap: a concealed archive chamber was destroyed selectively, with at least one sealed iron lockbox preserved and the corridor continued in use afterward.
Whether the Gap reflects operational security (three ledgers would create a complete record of something that needed to remain incomplete), institutional panic, or deliberate reputation management is contested.
The Reformist Adept Circle at the Keep argues that the Gap's existence proves the triple-ledger system was subverted from within; the Sanctum Continuity Office argues the Gap protected the Keep from external threats.
Scholars from Midgaard's Lantern Registry who have examined Gap-adjacent documents note that the missing witness entries correspond temporally to Violet Compact sealed-warrant activity.
The Gap's chronology places it during the Keep's Foyer Reform period — the same era when access segmentation and cipher systems were introduced, and when records suggest at least one major information leak prompted institutional lockdown.
The consequence ledger's destruction means the full scale of whatever occurred during the Gap cannot be determined from surviving records alone.
The Warm Obsidian Clock — an artifact in the Keep's sealed northern corridor — may be connected to the Gap: its warming cycle on a schedule that matches no current lock-cycle suggests something in the sealed space is still operating.

